\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {paragraph}{(c) RFT polishes consistency but kills pass@$k$.}{21}{paragraph*.48}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {16}{\ignorespaces RFT polishes consistency at the cost of pass@$k$. Per-turn metrics improve; per-task variance collapses; pass@3 regresses by 17\,pp. For deployment with sampling, the model's variance \emph  {is} the inference-scaling budget. \textit  {Note on notation.} \textbf  {mean@1} is the expected pass-rate of a single random sample, computed as the mean accuracy across the three sampling seeds (one $T{=}0$ greedy + two $T{=}0.7$). This is the natural variance-sensitive metric and differs from the greedy single-seed \emph  {pass@1}=44\% reported in \Cref  {tab:distill-headline,tab:distill-ablation}, which is just seed\nobreakspace  {}1's accuracy. \emph  {pass@2} and \emph  {pass@3} are union pass-rates over the first 2 / all 3 seeds.\relax }}{22}{table.caption.49}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:distill-rft}{{16}{22}{RFT polishes consistency at the cost of pass@$k$. Per-turn metrics improve; per-task variance collapses; pass@3 regresses by 17\,pp. For deployment with sampling, the model's variance \emph {is} the inference-scaling budget. \textit {Note on notation.} \textbf {mean@1} is the expected pass-rate of a single random sample, computed as the mean accuracy across the three sampling seeds (one $T{=}0$ greedy + two $T{=}0.7$). This is the natural variance-sensitive metric and differs from the greedy single-seed \emph {pass@1}=44\% reported in \Cref {tab:distill-headline,tab:distill-ablation}, which is just seed~1's accuracy. \emph {pass@2} and \emph {pass@3} are union pass-rates over the first 2 / all 3 seeds.\relax }{table.caption.49}{}}
\newlabel{tab:distill-rft@cref}{{[table][16][]16}{[1][21][]22}}
